5.1. Discussion on countermeasures on practical attacks
As it is previously shown in Table 12 the performance of authentication can be improved by incorporating additional biometrics in the authentication system, i.e. the use of multimodal biometrics. Multimodal biometrics-based authentication produces more consistent and higher authentication accuracy in comparison with the single biometrics-based authentication and achieves upgraded performance [24]. Many research works and practical implementations widely adopted the multimodal-based framework since the reliable authentication of a high level cannot be guaranteed by the single biometric [5], [9]. A plethora of studies have emphasized the superiority of multimodal biometric approaches to single biometric methods [77], [78], [79], [80], [81]. Since multimodal biometrics is performing better a well-built authentication mechanism is necessary to ensure the successful implementation of multimodal user authentication.
6. Lessons learned, challenges and future trends in this area
Following, we present lessons learned, challenges and future trends regarding BBCA technology.
6.1. Lessons learned
Behavioral biometrics and CA technology advantages: CA technology is a promising method with many advantages. It can perform without user intervention, it doesn't require additional hardware and it presents high accuracy for zero-effort evaluation approach.
Inconsistent behavior of the legitimate user: a major deficiency that results from the inconsistent interaction of users with their mobile phones is the unreliable performance [11]. In addition, a physical injury or a panic situation may result in behavioral changes, which can lead to inconsistent reactions by the legitimate user. Therefore, the appropriate management of unexpected situations must be established [52].
Changes in user behavior and habits: User behaviors and habits may change over time; thus, authentication systems should be able to adapt to these changes. The paradigm of Continual learning [163], [167], [168] can train successfully deep discriminative models as well as deep generative models in complex continual learning scenarios where new tasks appear, and existing tasks change over time. Therefore, this paradigm could be employed towards this direction.
Research data collection procedure: Many users avoid participating in time consuming, painstaking procedures for the collection of biometric features. This results in not fulfilling the data collection procedure.
Aspects of machine learning on mobile devices: Machine learning on mobile devices involves several aspects such as the amount of data from each user that is necessary for each approach to be effective, the computational and communication cost, and the usage of battery, memory, and CPU. When an authentication approach is evaluated, these aspects should be weighted and reported. Most researchers do not measure the aforementioned aspects in their work; thus, we cannot make a comparison of each method based on these aspects. We believe that future research should measure those aspects to enable the comparison.
Evaluation metrics: research works should weight and include at least the following metrics: FAR, TAR, FRR, EER, and Accuracy when evaluating the performance of their approach. In this way, it will be feasible to make a comparison between the approaches.
Vulnerabilities resulting from population statistics and users clustering: an adversary can gather information from the general population and efficiently mimic the typing patterns of the targeted individual subsequently avoiding the process of monitoring him by using, for example, a malware [59], [146], [150]. The adversary can additionally employ advanced robots, to make the attack even more successful [59], [144]. Also, the unique typing style of an individual belongs to a greater group of similar styles therefore the employment of adversarial agents such as the Targeted and the Indiscriminate K-means++ as shown in [146], can render the attack efficient.
Security in behavioural biometrics authentication: The primary menace is that the legitimate user's behaviour can be mimicked directly or indirectly by an impostor. Security in behavioural biometrics authentication can be improved if features are added or behavioural biometrics are combined with other biometrics or with non-biometrics.
6.2. Challenges
6.2.1. Behavioral Biometrics collection and feature extraction
Need for a user-friendly BB collection methodology: A major challenge is the design of a methodology for collecting behavioral biometrics, in a way that makes it user-friendly. The selection and optimization of a proper set of behavioral biometrics constitutes a challenge and an open problem.
Lack of real-world datasets: Another great challenge is the small number of real-world datasets. Besides, the availability of a public behavioral biometrics database for research purposes is necessary [10].
6.2.2. Systems evaluation
Maximizing accuracy: As we examined in the literature most studies implement approaches using machine learning algorithms but very few use deep machine learning. We consider that the accuracy of an authentication system based on behavioral biometrics must be tested with deep machine learning algorithms to examine if the performance can be increased.
Need for high-effort evaluation approach: Most of the works presented in this paper are using the zero-effort approach to evaluate the performance of their authentication systems. There is a need to direct the evaluation approach from the zero-effort to a high-effort to see the actual performance of the systems in the light of today's possible threats.
Changes in user behavior and habits: The paradigm of Continual learning [163], [167], [168] can be used to successfully train deep discriminative models as well as deep generative models in complex continual learning scenarios where new tasks appear, and existing tasks change over time. This will help towards the direction of solving the issue of authentication systems to adapting to changes in user behavior and habits.
6.2.3. Security and usability
Balance between security and usability: Behavioral biometrics authentication is subject to limitations, such as risk of false positives/false negatives, balance between security and usability, privacy concerns, etc., which result to its limited applicability. To overcome these limitations, it is crucial to maximize accuracy and examine how to find a balance between security and usability [112], [113].
Defense against Robotic attacks: Robotic attacks constitute an open problem on touch-based authentication systems [59], [144]. Adversaries can execute an effective robotic attack with cheap, off the shelf equipment and basic knowledge of programming. When combined with access to population statistics the attack becomes even more effective. With this threat case in mind, we suggest that a thorough evaluation of touch-based authentication systems should commence and proceed with research on technologies that could defend against robotic attacks.
Defense against mimicking attacks: Keystroke-based authentication systems are vulnerable to mimicking attacks. Attackers can use bots, crowdsourcing platforms, unsuspecting users or publicly available datasets to access keystroke data, extract keystroke feature statistics and launch an attack. As these attacks are highly effective there is a need for research on technologies that can defend against such attacks.
Systems resistance to real attacks: In chapter 5 we have presented possible countermeasures on practical attacks techniques on behavioral biometrics. The methods presented indeed improve the performance of the authentication systems but do not show the improvement of the systems resistance to real attacks. We believe that the performance of systems against trained imposters should be tested.
Maximizing systems reliability: The performance of behavioral biometrics authentication can be enhanced with the combination of different modalities. The superiority of multimodal biometric approaches in comparison with single biometric methods is emphasized in a plethora of studies. These approaches must be further tested in real-world large datasets since they are considered as the most reliable and secure.
6.2.4. Technology acceptance
Determinants of end-users’ acceptance: End users' perception and behavior constitute important considerations when designing systems since security, privacy and online identity management issues often trouble consumers. A study aimed at identifying non-technical issues, for example perceptions about the fears and expectations of future end-users, may be necessary for developing a strategy to support the acceptance of an innovation [147]. For these reasons, the assessment of technology acceptance determinants is crucial for addressing the problem of reduced use and utilization of the BBCA technology benefits.
6.3. Future trends
A large corpus of research has shown evidence regarding the superiority of the fusion of multimodal biometric approaches. A variety of combinations is used with the fusion of biometrics that achieves improved results compared to the single modality methods [24], [53]. Thus, the fusion of multimodal biometrics authentication emerges as a definite future trend. There is also evidence that the fusion of multimodal biometrics in combination with the Zero Interaction Authentication (ZIA) paradigm may also be a trend.
6.4. Summary and conclusions
In the present survey, we investigate Behavioral Biometrics and Continuous Authentication technologies for mobile devices to offer an up-to-date, comprehensive, extensive and targeted survey. The review of a large corpus of research in the field of BBCA technology has shown that CA technology can provide high authentication accuracy. Though, most of these works have used the zero-effort evaluation approaches. We believe that there is a need to shift from the zero-effort evaluation to the high-effort evaluation to see the actual performance of the systems under the spectrum of today's possible threats. Behavioral biometrics are promising but also vulnerable to practical attack schemes such as malware, mimic, impersonation, spoofing, replay, statistical, algorithmic and robotics attacks. The incorporation of additional biometrics in the authentication system, i.e. the use of multimodal authentication, is shown to improve security and guarantee reliable authentication. The superiority of multimodal biometric approaches to single biometric methods is emphasized in a plethora of studies. These approaches must be further tested in real-world, large datasets. Also, behavioral biometrics authentication is of limited extent due to some major shortcomings: risk of false positives/false negatives, the balance between security and usability, privacy concerns, etc. [1]. To overcome these shortcomings, it is critical to maximize accuracy and investigate how to balance security with usability. Since the behavior and habits of users may change over time, authentication systems should be able to adapt to these changes. In complex continual learning scenarios where new tasks appear, and existing tasks change over time the paradigm of Continual learning [163], [167], [168] could be employed to train successfully deep discriminative models as well as deep generative models. Therefore, this paradigm could constitute a solution. Also, most researchers do not measure the amount of data from each user that is necessary for each approach to be effective, the computational and communication cost, and the usage of battery, memory, and CPU in their work. Thus, we cannot make a comparison of each method based on these aspects. Future research should measure those aspects to enable the comparison. In addition, when researchers evaluate the performance of their approach, they should at least weight and report the following metrics: FAR, TAR, FRR, EER, and Accuracy. In this way, it will be feasible to make a comparison between the approaches. Finally, evaluating end-users’ technology acceptance determinants is vital to addressing the problem of reduced use of BBCA technology. Finally, a major challenge is the testing of a methodology for extracting biometric features, in a way that makes it user friendly, because many users avoid participating in time consuming, painstaking procedures for the collection of biometric features. We hope that this article will trigger researchers and practitioners towards the investigation of open problems and challenges in this field.
